Stock Terminology

Little bit more about shorting
- Short positions can outweigh total number
of public shares.
- Example: P1 borrows a share from P2, and in turn
lends it to P3. Now there is 1 share, but 2 short
positions on it.

Risky, but if short works out, you can benefit quite
a bit so such positions are fairly common,
esp. by hedge funds.
Setting some context
- We've all had a pretty weird year
    Covid Lockdowns
    Stimulus Checks
    Robinhood app (USA ka Zerodha/Groww)
   


... And all this while, the rich have gotten richer
GameStop ($GME) Fundamentals
- Video Game retailer in America
- Part of childhood for a lot of gamers


- Outdated business model
- Bad financial performance
- Lack of innovation
- Easy target for shorting, with some hedge funds like
Melvin Capital holding large short positions. In fact, it
becomes one of the most widely shorted stocks.
Enter /r/WallStreetBets
WallStreetBets (WSB) is a  subreddit where people
discuss all things stock.

Members range from real-life traders, teenagers who
spout pseudo-economic theories, people shilling penny
stocks and what not. Add in a tonne of memes, a dash of
crude, racism/homophobia. (x 2M members).
"YOLO"                                            
The Beginning
-WSB identifies that the outstanding $GME short
positions is > 140+% of the publicly traded shares
of the company.

- This means there's a lot of big money betting that
the stock will fall in price.

- But remember that shorting needs you to return
the "borrowed stock". Can we prevent that from
happening? 

One of the early guys to identify this was in Jul 2020: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GZTr1-Gp74U
And the Short Squeeze begins
- Through a tonne of YOLO, and messages,
WSB push each other to buy and hold as much $GME
stock as possible.
- The stock is trading at $10-15 but the unofficial
target price to hold is called out as $420.69

This causes a two-fold effect:
- Since there is demand for the stock in market,
stock price goes up.
- Since price is going up, hedge funds need to buy $GME
to close their short positions as a premium, further
driving prices up further.
(if you get it, you get it)
Hold, Hold, Hold!
- Share Prices start hitting growing 40%+ daily,
but noone sells. Cycle has begun. WSB members keep
buying up as much public stock as possible.

- Media Coverage >>> More retail investors join in.

Big Boys join in
London Bridge is falling down!
- In 2 weeks, $GME hits $450. Then things collapse:

- Robinhood bans trading of $GME and other "meme"
stocks (like $NOK, $AMC and $BB)

- The moment $420.69 is breached, half the people start
dumping, while other half pushes for holding for longer,
causing massive volatility.

- News comes in of Melvin and other hedge funds
closing out their short positions. Even more confusion.
When the dust settled
Tendies
Where's Dalal Street Bets?
TL;DR Not Happening.

- GSM prevents wild swinging of stocks, esp. Small Cap

- Shorting is both Philosphically and Systemically
shunned (20% of free float is the maximum
speculative position)

- How brokerages/funds make money is different.
Retail investors get cleaner data in India because TXN
fees, not order data drives revenues.
* There is a /r/dalalstreetbets/ that does a lot of speculatory stuff though
